dges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Henry","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Hunte","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Especially North America: transferred use of the surname, in origin an occupational name. The term was used not only of hunters on horseback of game such as stags and wild boars, which was in the Middle Ages a pursuit restricted to the ranks of the nobility, but also of much humbler bird catchers and poachers seeking food."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Thomas Henry Hunte was born in 1320 as the son of Gilbertus Hunt de Stoke and Matilda Ridol. He had at least 1 son with Eden de Stafford. He died in 1358, at the age of 38."},"et":{"1320–1358":"1320–1358","–Female":"Surnud","1355–1437":"1355–1437","1305–1325":"1305–1325","1305":"1305","1437":"1437","1325":"1325","1358":"1358","1355":"1355","1320":"1320","Gosfield, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Gosfield, Essex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1320–1358":"132